data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 6+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — the entire abort mechanism is gone
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime

The old pattern relied on cooperative-via-force cancellation. .NET 8 requires fully cooperative cancellation using `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handling
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit cleanly — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal cooperative cancellation
        await _cts.CancelAsync();  // .NET 8+; use Cancel() on older targets

        // Wait with timeout — replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)))
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort(). You cannot force-kill it.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()` ignores cancellation** | If the old method blocks on a `Queue`/socket without a token, cancellation can't interrupt it. Migrate to async APIs (`Channel<T>`, async I/O) or pass `CancellationToken`. |
| **No force-kill exists** | `Thread.Abort()` has no replacement. If code hangs in unmanaged/blocking calls, you're stuck. Design all waits to accept a `CancellationToken`. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` silently disappears** | The old catch block just stops running — partial work may go unrolled-back if you don't add `OperationCanceledException` handling. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Remove it entirely. `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — no re-throw suppression needed. |
| **`volatile bool` is still fine but insufficient** | It can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` can, via callback registration or token-aware APIs. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run` loses exceptions** | Unobserved exceptions vanish. Store the `Task` and `await` it in `StopAsync`/`DisposeAsync`. |

### If You Can't Make `GetNextItem` Async

Wrap the synchronous blocking call so cancellation still works:

```csharp
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Runs blocking call on thread pool but respects cancellation
    return await Task.Run(() =>
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        return GetNextItem(); // legacy blocking call
    }, token);
}
```

> ⚠️ This won't interrupt `GetNextItem()` mid-block — it only checks cancellation before entry. Prefer migrating to `Channel<T>.ReadAsync()` or similar token-aware APIs for true interruption.
